<div align="center"><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="3">&nbsp;<font size="4">&nbsp;Enrico 
  Falconi</font><br>
  &nbsp;writer/producer/director/editor</font></div>
<div align="center"> <font size="3" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><br>
  </font> 
  <p align="left"><font size="3" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">Enrico &#8220;Henri&#8221; 
    Falconi was introduced to filmmaking while studying drama and photography 
    at Santa Barbara City College. In 1987, he was cast in the award winning, 
    SBCC, production of Neil Simon&#8217;s, Biloxi Blues, and has worked in film, 
    theatre and television, ever since. He received a certificate in film, from 
    New York University&#8217;s, Film, Theatre &amp; Broadcasting program in 1996. 
    To date he&#8217;s worked on over 40 short and feature films in almost every 
    capacity. In 1995 Enrico worked at the I.F.P. as the shorts screening coordinator 
    for the Independent Feature Film Market in New York. In 1996 he curated a 
    short film series, the Falcon Film Fiesta, an overwhelming success, it played 
    to sold out audiences at Anthology Film Archives and the New York Film Academy. 
    <br>
    <br>
    At the age of 27, Enrico found his calling as an auteur with his debut, 20 
    minute, short, Thinking About Chocolate, (IFFM/96, Albany International Short 
    Film Fest/96, The New Filmmaker&#8217;s Forum at the SLIFF/96). That fall, 
    he was the 2nd assistant director on Darren Aronofsky&#8217;s, Pi (Winner 
    - Sundance Film Festival &#8216;98: Best Director; Independent Spirit Awards 
    &#8216;99: First Screenplay). (Enrico also had a small role in Pi, as one 
    of the Cabala Scholars). In 1999, he co-produced, edited &amp; acted in, Man 
    Woman Film, a $40.000, 16mm, B&amp;W feature film, featuring Cameron Diaz. 
    Written and directed by Cameron Pearson, it has appeared in over twenty international 
    film festivals and was being considered for participation in the Quinzaine 
    Realisateurs (Director&#8217;s Fortnight) at Cannes 2000, only to be disqualified 
    for having already screened around the world. <br>
    <br>
    Enrico is the author of three screenplays: The Beer run, Between Days &amp; 
    How Much To Manhattan? He has written, directed, produced and edited six short 
    films: Alsjeblieft-2005, Original Black Poet-2003, 1937-2002, Go To Jail-2002, 
    Angry Jenkins&#8217;Farm-2001 and Thinking About Chocolate-1996, He is also 
    in his 13th year of filming a digital documentary: Experience, a unique concert 
    film chronicling the life and career of virtuoso Gypsy jazz guitarist, Robin 
    Nolan. <br>
    <br>
    Enrico was born in Veracruz, Mexico, in 1969 he arrived in the East Village 
    of New York City, where he still lives, with his cats Charlie &amp; Max. He 
    is currently in development on Cannes, sir, slated to shoot entirely on Location 
    at the Cannes film festival, it&#8217;s a psycho sensual homage that&#8217;s 
    guaranteed to arouse even the most cynical of cinephiles.</font> </p>
